{{Distinguish|Massive Entertainment}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}} {{Infobox company | name = Massive Development | logo = Massive Development logo.png | type = {{Unbulleted list|[[Privately held company|Private]]|{{small|(October 1994-13 December 2000)}}|[[Subsidiary]] of [[JoWooD]]|{{small|(14 December 2000 – 30 May 2005)}}}} | founded = {{start date and age|df=yes|1994|10}} | defunct = {{end date|df=yes|2005|05|30}} | location = [[Mannheim]], [[Germany]] | key_people = {{Unbulleted list|Alexander Jorias|Ingo Frick|Oliver Weirich}} | num_employees = 15 | num_employees_year = 2005 | industry = [[Video games industry]] | products = [[Video game]]s | homepage = [https://web.archive.org/web/20050913152727/http://www.massive.de/ Massive.de] (archived) }}
'''Massive Development GmbH''' was a [[video game developer]] based in [[Mannheim]], [[Germany]]. Founded as '''Massive Development GbR''', the company was active between 1994 and 2005 and is primarily known for their [[Apocalyptic and post-apocalyptic fiction|post-apocalyptic]] [[science fiction]] video games ''[[Archimedean Dynasty]]'' and ''[[AquaNox]]'', which have attained somewhat of a [[cult status]].
== History == Massive Development was founded in 1994 by Alexander Jorias, Ingo Frick and Oliver Weirich in Mannheim as Massive Development GbR. Their first product was the porting of the [[Amiga]] game ''[[The Settlers]]'' to [[MS-DOS]] in 1994. In 1996 they released the successful [[science-fiction]] [[submarine]] [[Role-playing game|role-playing]] [[video game]] ''Archimedean Dynasty'', published by [[Blue Byte]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=2428 | title = Power Play 12/96, Seiten 76-78 | author = jamyz1102 | website = [[Kultboy.com]] | language = DE | accessdate = 17 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.massive.de/project_sf/sf_press_d.html | title = Schleichfahrt - Presseberichte - Deutschland | date = 30 October 1996 | website = Massive Development | language = DE | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20011116231929/http://www.massive.de/project_sf/sf_press_d.html | archivedate = 16 November 2001 | accessdate = 17 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://corny.silentdepth.com/Downloads/sfmanual.pdf | title = Schleichfahrt - Vom Tageslicht vergessen, von der Finsternis beherrscht! | author = Massive Development | date = 2000 | website = [[SilentDepth.com]] | language = DE | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120317081231/http://corny.silentdepth.com/Downloads/sfmanual.pdf | archivedate = 17 March 2012 |accessdate = 17 November 2015}}</ref>
In December 2000, Massive Development was bought by the Austrian publisher [[JoWooD]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.massive.de/news/news_d.shtml | title = News und Presseerklärungen - JoWood [PE] | last = Reis | first = Thomas | date = 14 December 2000 | website = Massive Development | publisher = [[JoWooD]] | language = DE | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20010203192600/http://www.massive.de/news/news_d.shtml | archivedate = 3 February 2001 | accessdate = 17 November 2015}}</ref> Until 2000, Massive Development worked on its own game engine called "krass Engine", which was used for their next title ''[[AquaNox#AquaNox|AquaNox]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.massive.de/project_kr/krass_tec_d.html | title = krass(tm) Engine - Technische Details | date = 2000 | website = Massive Development | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20020415004053/http://www.massive.de/project_kr/krass_tec_d.html | archivedate = 15 April 2002}}</ref> It was one of the first games to make use of the new capabilities of [[graphic card]]s with [[T&L]] hardware, which is why ''AquaNox'' was also [[Product bundling|bundled]] with new graphic cards. On 30 May 2005, the development studio was closed by JoWooD,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mediabiz.de/games/news/jowood-schliesst-studio/179709 | title = JoWooD schließt Studio | author = Rottenmann | date = 30 May 2005 | website = [[mediabiz.de]] | publisher = [[Busch Entertainment Media]] | language = DE | accessdate = 17 November 2015}}</ref> and by that cancelling the development of ''[[AquaNox#AquaNox: The Angel's Tears|AquaNox: The Angel's Tears]]'' for the [[PlayStation 2]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://jj.bravo795.server4you.de/ | title = Kein AquaNox: The Angel's Tears ! | author = Impossible | date = 24 September 2007 | website = [[AquaNox World]] | language = DE | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070925130640/http://jj.bravo795.server4you.de/ | archivedate = 25 September 2007 | accessdate = 17 November 2015}}</ref>
Two of the original founders, Alexander Jorias and Ingo Frick, are now working on a 3D chat with Social Networking Features, titled ''Club Cooee''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://gamebizz.de/interview-mit-stefan-lemper-von-club-cooee | title = Interview mit Stefan Lemper von Club Cooee | date = 19 April 2010 | website = [[GameBizz.de]] | language = DE | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110817000223/http://gamebizz.de/interview-mit-stefan-lemper-von-club-cooee | archivedate = 17 August 2011 | accessdate = 17 November 2015}}</ref>
== Developed games == * ''[[The Settlers (video game)|The Settlers]]'' ([[MS-DOS]] port) (1994) - released in [[Germany]] under its original title ''Die Siedler'', and in the [[United States]] as ''Serf City: Life is Feudal'' * ''[[AquaNox#Archimedean Dynasty|Archimedean Dynasty]]'' (1996) - released in Germany under its original title ''Schleichfahrt'' * ''[[krass Engine]]'' (2001) - engine of the ''[[AquaNox]]'' series and ''[[SpellForce]]'', and [[middleware]] of ''[[Legend of Kay]]'' * ''[[AquaNox#AquaNox|AquaNox]]'' (2001) * ''[[AquaNox#AquaNox 2: Revelation|AquaNox 2: Revelation]]'' (2003) * ''[[AquaNox#AquaNox: The Angel's Tears|AquaNox: The Angel's Tears]]'' (canceled)
