{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}} {{multiple issues| {{more citations needed|date=February 2011}} {{cleanup|date=February 2011}} }} {{Infobox company | name = THQ Studio Australia | logo = THQ-Studio-Australia logo.gif | caption = | type = [[Subsidiary]] of [[THQ]] | slogan = | foundation = 2003 | defunct = August 2011 | location = [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]] | industry = [[Video game industry|Software & Programming]] | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | owner = [[THQ]] | num_employees = 200 | parent = [[THQ]] | homepage = http://www.thqstudioaustralia.com/ }}
'''THQ Studio Australia''' was one of the subsidiaries of electronic game publisher [[THQ]]. Based in [[Brisbane]] [[Australia]], the studio have developed titles for the [[Sixth generation of video game consoles|Sixth]] and [[Seventh generation of video game consoles|Seventh]] generation of games consoles and managed (via internal producers) the development of hand held versions of their games utilizing smaller local and interstate development studios.
==History== THQ Studio Australia was founded in 2003 and concentrated on developing titles based on popular [[Nickelodeon (TV channel)|Nickelodeon]] TV licenses. Releasing a new title yearly between 2004 and 2008 before expanding into multiple teams and developing movie tie in games such as [[The Last Airbender (video game)]] based on [[M night|M. Night Shyamalan's]] 2010 movie [[The Last Airbender]] and their last developed game release of [[Dreamworks animation|DreamWorks Animation's]] [[Megamind]] movie.
In August, 2011, THQ Studio Australia was announced to be closed down as part of a restructuring and realignment plan by parent company, THQ.
